<subSubSection lastPageId="11" lastPageNumber="358" pageId="10" pageNumber="357" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="10.[151,1127,1330,1578]" pageId="10" pageNumber="357">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,268,1330,1354]" pageId="10" pageNumber="357">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Hartig" baseAuthorityYear="1841" box="[273,525,1331,1354]" class="Insecta" family="Figitidae" genus="Alloxysta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="357" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="macrophadna">
<emphasis box="[273,525,1331,1354]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="357">Alloxysta macrophadna</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is characterized by partially open radial cell, presence of pronotal carinae, and absence of propodeal carinae. In 
<collectingCountry box="[744,996,1362,1387]" name="Serbia" pageId="10" pageNumber="357">Serbia and Montenegro</collectingCountry>
it is similar to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Belizin" authorityYear="1973" box="[180,314,1395,1418]" class="Insecta" family="Figitidae" genus="Alloxysta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="357" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="salicicola">
<emphasis box="[180,314,1395,1418]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="357">A. salicicola</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but they can be easily differentiated by (i) the proportion of the lengths of flagellomeres: F2–F4 not subequal in 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Hartig" baseAuthorityYear="1841" box="[549,725,1427,1450]" class="Insecta" family="Figitidae" genus="Alloxysta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="357" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="macrophadna">
<emphasis box="[549,725,1427,1450]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="357">A. macrophadna</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[738,814,1426,1450]" captionStart="Figs 15–24" captionStartId="6.[151,188,1493,1512]" captionTargetBox="[191,1087,219,1470]" captionTargetId="figure-10@6.[191,1087,219,1470]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Figs 15–24. Antenna of Alloxysta species. 15 – A. castanea (Hartig, 1841); 16 – A. macrophadna (Hartig, 1841); 17 – A. mullensis (Cameron, 1883); 18 – A. victrix (Westwood, 1833); 19 – A. arcuata (Kieffer, 1902); 20 – A. fracticornis (Thomson, 1862); 21 – A. brevis (Thomson, 1862); 22 – A. fuscicornis (Hartig, 1841); 23 – A. pleuralis (Cameron, 1879); 24 – A. salicicola Belizin, 1973." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5740346" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5740346/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="357">Fig. 16</figureCitation>
) but subequal in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Belizin" authorityYear="1973" box="[994,1127,1427,1450]" class="Insecta" family="Figitidae" genus="Alloxysta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="357" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="salicicola">
<emphasis box="[994,1127,1427,1450]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="357">A. salicicola</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[159,238,1458,1482]" captionStart="Figs 15–24" captionStartId="6.[151,188,1493,1512]" captionTargetBox="[191,1087,219,1470]" captionTargetId="figure-10@6.[191,1087,219,1470]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Figs 15–24. Antenna of Alloxysta species. 15 – A. castanea (Hartig, 1841); 16 – A. macrophadna (Hartig, 1841); 17 – A. mullensis (Cameron, 1883); 18 – A. victrix (Westwood, 1833); 19 – A. arcuata (Kieffer, 1902); 20 – A. fracticornis (Thomson, 1862); 21 – A. brevis (Thomson, 1862); 22 – A. fuscicornis (Hartig, 1841); 23 – A. pleuralis (Cameron, 1879); 24 – A. salicicola Belizin, 1973." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5740346" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5740346/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="357">Fig. 24</figureCitation>
); and by (ii) size of radial cell: 3.3 times as long as wide in 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Hartig" baseAuthorityYear="1841" box="[865,1041,1459,1482]" class="Insecta" family="Figitidae" genus="Alloxysta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="357" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="macrophadna">
<emphasis box="[865,1041,1459,1482]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="357">A. macrophadna</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[1055,1118,1458,1482]" captionStart="Figs 5–14" captionStartId="5.[113,150,1493,1512]" captionTargetBox="[143,1063,220,1470]" captionTargetId="figure-15@5.[137,1066,217,1473]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="Figs 5–14. Types of radial cell in forewing of Alloxysta species. 5 – A. castanea (Hartig, 1841); 6 – A. macrophadna (Hartig, 1841); 7 – A. pleuralis (Cameron, 1879); 8 – A. mullensis (Cameron, 1883); 9 – A. victrix (Westwood, 1833); 10 – A. fracticornis (Thomson, 1862); 11 – A. arcuata (Kieffer, 1902); 12 – A. brevis (Thomson, 1862); 13 – A. fuscicornis (Hartig, 1841); 14 – A. salicicola Belizin, 1973." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5740344" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5740344/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="357">Fig. 6</figureCitation>
) whereas it is 2.6 times as long as wide in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Belizin" authorityYear="1973" box="[593,727,1491,1514]" class="Insecta" family="Figitidae" genus="Alloxysta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="357" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="salicicola">
<emphasis box="[593,727,1491,1514]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="357">A. salicicola</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[741,821,1490,1514]" captionStart="Figs 5–14" captionStartId="5.[113,150,1493,1512]" captionTargetBox="[143,1063,220,1470]" captionTargetId="figure-15@5.[137,1066,217,1473]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="Figs 5–14. Types of radial cell in forewing of Alloxysta species. 5 – A. castanea (Hartig, 1841); 6 – A. macrophadna (Hartig, 1841); 7 – A. pleuralis (Cameron, 1879); 8 – A. mullensis (Cameron, 1883); 9 – A. victrix (Westwood, 1833); 10 – A. fracticornis (Thomson, 1862); 11 – A. arcuata (Kieffer, 1902); 12 – A. brevis (Thomson, 1862); 13 – A. fuscicornis (Hartig, 1841); 14 – A. salicicola Belizin, 1973." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5740344" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5740344/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="357">Fig. 14</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="10.[151,1127,1330,1578]" lastBlockId="11.[113,1089,219,500]" lastPageId="11" lastPageNumber="358" pageId="10" pageNumber="357">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,377,1522,1546]" pageId="10" pageNumber="357">Short redescription.</emphasis>
Head yellowish red, mesosoma and metasoma dark brown; scape, pedicel and F1–F3 yellow, the remaining ones brown yellowish; legs yellow; veins dark brown. Female antennae 13-segmented; F1–F3 smooth and thinner than remaining ones, F4–F11 club-shaped, with rhinaria; F1 longer than pedicel, F1 longer than F2, F2 shorter than F3, and F3 shorter than F4 (
<figureCitation box="[374,455,283,307]" captionStart="Figs 15–24" captionStartId="6.[151,188,1493,1512]" captionTargetBox="[191,1087,219,1470]" captionTargetId="figure-10@6.[191,1087,219,1470]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Figs 15–24. Antenna of Alloxysta species. 15 – A. castanea (Hartig, 1841); 16 – A. macrophadna (Hartig, 1841); 17 – A. mullensis (Cameron, 1883); 18 – A. victrix (Westwood, 1833); 19 – A. arcuata (Kieffer, 1902); 20 – A. fracticornis (Thomson, 1862); 21 – A. brevis (Thomson, 1862); 22 – A. fuscicornis (Hartig, 1841); 23 – A. pleuralis (Cameron, 1879); 24 – A. salicicola Belizin, 1973." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5740346" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5740346/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="358">Fig. 16</figureCitation>
). Male antennae 14-segmented; F1–F2 smooth and thinner than remaining ones, F3–F12 club-shaped, with rhinaria; F2 and F3 clearly curved; F1 longer than pedicel, F1 subequal to F2, F2 longer than F3, and F3 longer than F4. Pronotum densely covered with short setae, with two long carinae under the pubescence. Propodeum without carinae, densely covered by setae. Forewing longer than body, radial cell partially open, 3.3 times as long as wide (
<figureCitation box="[356,422,443,467]" captionStart="Figs 5–14" captionStartId="5.[113,150,1493,1512]" captionTargetBox="[143,1063,220,1470]" captionTargetId="figure-15@5.[137,1066,217,1473]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="Figs 5–14. Types of radial cell in forewing of Alloxysta species. 5 – A. castanea (Hartig, 1841); 6 – A. macrophadna (Hartig, 1841); 7 – A. pleuralis (Cameron, 1879); 8 – A. mullensis (Cameron, 1883); 9 – A. victrix (Westwood, 1833); 10 – A. fracticornis (Thomson, 1862); 11 – A. arcuata (Kieffer, 1902); 12 – A. brevis (Thomson, 1862); 13 – A. fuscicornis (Hartig, 1841); 14 – A. salicicola Belizin, 1973." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5740344" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5740344/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="358">Fig. 6</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
